  "final_answer": "## Il Messaggero's Coverage of Mussolini's Fall and the Badoglio Transition (July 25-27, 1943)\n\nIl Messaggero's coverage of this pivotal moment reveals a dramatic editorial shift that occurred literally overnight. The July 25, 1943 issue contains no mention of the regime change, as the announcement came late that evening after the paper had gone to press. The front page of July 25 focused on routine war news—Soviet attacks on the Eastern Front and Pacific naval operations—with no hint of the political earthquake about to occur.\n\nThe transformation becomes strikingly evident in the July 27 issue (the July 26 issue is absent from the archive). The newspaper's tone underwent a complete metamorphosis. The lead story, \"La composizione del Governo Badoglio\" (1943-07-27_a000), describes \"Un'altra giornata di entusiastiche dimostrazioni di popolo acclamante all'Italia, alle Forze Armate, al Re e al Maresciallo\"—enthusiastic popular demonstrations for Italy, the Armed Forces, the King, and the Marshal.\n\nMost revealing is the detailed account in \"L'ordine del giorno e la votazione del Gran Consiglio nella riunione del 24\" (1943-07-27_a006), which matter-of-factly reports that the Gran Consiglio del Fascismo met on July 24 for the first time since December 7, 1939, and voted on Grandi's motion calling for restoration of constitutional functions to the Crown, Parliament, and other state bodies. The newspaper presents this as a legitimate constitutional process rather than a coup.\n\nThe editorial \"Carattere del nuovo Governo\" (1943-07-27_a040) exemplifies the new register. Gone is fascist rhetoric; instead, the paper praises Badoglio's government as one of \"decisive, strenuous military energy\" needed for \"the salvation of the country.\" It lauds individual ministers for their technical competence and integrity—particularly Carmine Senise's return as Police Chief, described as having \"profound sense of justice\" and abhorring anything \"not clear, humane and dignified.\"\n\nThe newspaper's coverage emphasized spontaneous popular enthusiasm. \"Adunate non preordinate ed entusiasmo senza retorica\" (1943-07-27_a066) describes how crowds spontaneously gathered on the night of July 25, singing Risorgimento hymns like Mameli's anthem and the \"Canzone del Piave,\" chanting \"Viva l'Italia Libera\" (Long Live Free Italy). The tricolor replaced fascist symbols.\n\nThis abrupt shift—from silence to celebration—demonstrates Il Messaggero's complete realignment within 48 hours, abandoning twenty years of fascist loyalty to embrace the monarchical-military government without hesitation or explanation.",
